<DOC><DOCNO> AP881214-0250 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-12-14-88 0836EST</FILEID><FIRST>r f PM-DroughtInsurance     12-14 0190</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Drought Insurance,0197</SECOND><HEAD>Chubb Reaches Settlement With Illinois Over Drought Insurance</HEAD><DATELINE>SPRINGFIELD, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Illinois has dropped administrativecharges against Chubb Corp. over the sale of drought insurance afterthe New Jersey company agreed to pay a $50,000 fine and the $100,000cost of a state probe.   State Insurance Director John Washburn announced the actionTuesday, four days after a federal judge in Cincinnati approved a$48 million drought insurance settlement for 8,800 farmers in 10states, including Illinois.   ``Chubb has acted very responsibly in agreeing to settle thisentire issue in such an expeditious manner,'' Washburn said.   ``As a result, the department's goal of obtaining coverage forall of the farmers who applied for this coverage was achieved, andwe resolved our administrative proceedings and concluded this matterat no expense to Illinois taxpayers,'' he said.   Federal Insurance Co., a subsidiary of Chubb, was cited for nineviolations of Illinois law in administrative charges filed inOctober.   The company was accused of selling insurance against inadequaterain to farmers who thought they were buying coverage fordrought-related crop losses. The policy is not allowed by state law.</TEXT></DOC>